President Obama and President Karzai held a one-hour video teleconference where they discussed various topics, including the transition to Afghan security lead, strategic partnership negotiations, and the recent Koran burning and resulting violence in Afghanistan. President Obama commended President Karzai's announcement of the first tranche of provinces and municipalities to transition to Afghan lead. Both leaders emphasized the importance of achieving peace in Afghanistan through progress on transition, a lasting U.S.-Afghan strategic partnership, and reconciliation. They also expressed their condemnation of the desecration of the Koran and the attack on UNAMA in Mazar-e-Sharif, and their deep regret for the loss of life. The two presidents agreed that it is a time for their nations to unite in pursuit of common values and goals.